\begin_layout Subsection*
Individual Contributor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you don’t start your career as a manager, you begin at Milestone 0: individua
l contributor.
 This is where you hone your technical abilities.
 This is where you learn the ins and outs of your job.
 This is where you experience first hand how one part of the organization
 works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As your skills develop, you get better at your job.
 You think of ways to do your job more easily and more effectively.
 You build a reputation as someone with leadership potential.
 At some point when people are deciding who should lead an upcoming initiative,
 your name comes up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Team Lead
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next milestone is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

team lead
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The best way of reaching this milestone is to take on the role after you've
 already established strong mutual respect and trust with team members.
 Here, the team recognizes your technical ability, your knack for keeping
 things running smoothly, and your potential to lead.
 The team implicitly trusts you and is already treating you as the 
\emph on
de facto
\emph default
 leader.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A harder, but more common way to become a team lead, is when your manager
 simply picks you for the role.
 Depending on the internal politics of the group, this may result in resentment
 and loss of morale.
 If this is the case, you’ll need to work hard at building trust within
 the team.
 This is work on top of your normal responsibilities, so it's important
 to understand this before you accept the role.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Team As Extension of Self
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third milestone is when you start viewing the team as an extension of
 yourself.
 This is a tricky time for a manager.
 As an individual contributor, you worked hard to excel and distance yourself
 from your peers.
 As a manager, it's natural to want to do the same with your team.
 Your focus will be on getting your team to perform better and execute faster,
 not because it's good for the org 
\emph on
per se
\emph default
, but in order to leave other teams behind.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many managers never get past this milestone.
 They jockey for position within the organization.
 They play politics to gain power.
 Their primary goal is to advance themselves, even at the organization's
 expense.
 These managers have lost their way.
 When you become a manager, you need to put the team before you and the
 organization before your team.
 If you consistently put yourself first, you will significantly limit the
 impact you can make.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Engaged Detachment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last milestone of a manager is something I call “engaged detachment”.
 Here, managers are 
\emph on
engaged
\emph default
 in the organization’s overall mission and goals, but are able to 
\emph on
detach
\emph default
 themselves emotionally from their situation so they can clearly see what
 needs to be done next to move their organizations forward.
 Sometimes this means doing things that are not in their best interests
 but which benefit the organization most (and ultimately themselves, too).
 Managers in this state see how the organization could and 
\emph on
should
\emph default
 work — outside of themselves — and have the courage to lead people there.
\end_layout

